Motivation

What is the price of making decisions made based on wrong data or gut feelings? How can one distill trends and predict a behavior from huge ocean of data to help make precise and timely decisions? The answer, very often, is costly and/or critically risky! In his ground braking book The Signal and the Noise, the renowned statistician and Data Scientist Nate Silver, discusses prediction of real word case studies, from cross section of industries, utilizing models based on probability and statistics.

On this paper, I will use statistical programming language R, statistical linear regression model and data visualization dynamic graphs to illuminate how data science can help separate signal (relevant data) from the noise (the rest of the data), to answer a specific question that may be used to craft a policy or assist in making a sound decision.

Scenario

I will use hypothetical scenario, and data obtained from UCLA Institute for Digital Research and Education. The data, presumably, is a sample of students test scores for reading, writing, math, science and social studies.

Suppose school district with with hundreds of thousands of junior and high school students performed poorly on standardized testing over all. Some of the students have done much worse than others. A school administrator sets out to improve the test scores. With diverse student cultures and different socioeconomic house holds, the school administrator wants to analyze the data from the test scores in order to identify groups with the most need and make the necessary programs available to help them. This will also help in his budget allocation.

Statistical random sampling is used to select the data for the analysis. Statistical sampling is not going to be covered here, but it has proven to be reliable to make accurate reading for the entire population trend. With acceptable margins of error.

The Question:

What is the performance of black female students who come from lower socio economic households performance in the math and science portion of the test?

Tidy the data

Before jumping to the analysis, the first order of business is to get and clean the data by structuring the dataset for robust facilitation of the analysis. The best practices of tidying the data uses standard way to construct the values in a dataset. Tidy data is data that is easier to model, analyze, aggregate and visualize. It has one feature (variable) per column and one observation per row. On this case, the data from UCLA comes in csv table format with variables and rows defined with no missing values.

To get the data ready, however, adding factors and labeling was helpful for making the analysis more intuitive. The following factors were added

  1. Set gender factor (0 = male, 1 = female)
  2. Set race factor (1 = Hispanic, 2 = Asian, 3 = Black, 4 = White)
  3. Set Socioeconomic class (1 = low income, 2 = middle income, 3 = high income) 4, Set School types (1 = public, 2 = private)

A second table was also created to summarized the average test scores by race and gender.

Look at the bottom of the page in the code section how this is performed.

Average test score by race and gender

The sample data contains for only 200 students, this is likely a random sample of a much larger student population. The following table summarizes & averages the respective scores for each of the five exams by race and gender.

Cross classification

We can add socio economic class, low/mid/high income, to the equation to drill deeper and get a more detailed profile of the students. This is because black female students from mid/high inome household who attend private schools tend to perform better and can skew the average test score for lower income black female students. Therefore, if we separate by race, gender and socio economic background, we can distill a better profile read for this group.

#cross-classifying factors brekdown by race and gender
    with(df2, table(race, gender))
##           gender
## race       female male
##   asian         8    3
##   black        13    7
##   hispanic     11   13
##   white        77   68
    with(df2, table(race, socioecon))
##           socioecon
## race       high low middle
##   asian       3   3      5
##   black       3  11      6
##   hispanic    4   9     11
##   white      48  24     73

Seprating the Signal from the Noise

The first plot shows the total sample population scatter plot for math and Science. Dplyr filter function is used to grab the black female students. They are identified with the orange color. However, these plots dont show which socio economic group the girls belong.

The following graphs split the black female students from the total population for easier contrast. This is where the signal and noise effect is visualised.

Visualizing the Data

The following plot answers the question raised at the outset. The graph uses the combinations of ggplot2 and plotly to make it dynamic, in that one can pan zoom and mouse over the points to see how black female students from lower socio economic households fare. By selecting/deselecting the points on the right side one can add/remove other races and socio groups to see the result in isolation.

plot that answers the question

Linear model plots

The following plot shows the linear regression model for all students and shows with light blue line the direction of the trend for each group. Once again, one can zoom, select/deselect to isolate parts of the data as needed.

Answer to the question:

Black female students from lower socio economic households score lower than all other races and socio economic groups save for black males. Therefor program focused on this demographic group in math and science is needed to help raise the overall standard.

# load the libs
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(knitr)
library(gridExtra)
library(plotly)

# set working dir
setwd("~/Documents/DataScience/Blogs/Blog6") 

# download and save the file in data sub dir
if(!file.exists("./data")){dir.create("./data")}
fileUrl <- "http://www.ats.ucla.edu/stat/data/hsb2.csv"
download.file(fileUrl, destfile = "./data/hsb2.csv", method = "curl")

# make csv to tbl data frame
hsb2 <- tbl_df(read.csv("./data/hsb2"))


# tidy the data
df1 <- hsb2 %>% 
# lable race                    
        mutate(race = as.factor(ifelse(race == 4, "white", 
                                ifelse(race == 3, "black", 
                                ifelse(race == 2, "asian", 
                                ifelse(race == 1, "hispanic", 
                                race
                                       ))))
                               )
               )                             %>%
# lable program type 
        mutate(progtyp  = as.factor(ifelse(prog == 3, "vocational", 
                                    ifelse(prog == 2, "academic", 
                                    ifelse(prog == 1, "general", 
                                           prog
                                             )))
                                    )
               )                             %>%
# Socio economic status of students   
        mutate(socioecon = as.factor(ifelse(ses == 3, "high", 
                                     ifelse(ses == 2, "middle", 
                                     ifelse(ses == 1, "low", 
                                            ses
                                                  )))
                                     )
               )                             %>%

# Gender       
        mutate (gender   = as.factor(ifelse(female   == "1" , "female", "male")))    %>%      

# School type 
        mutate (schltype = as.factor(ifelse(schtyp   == "1" , "public", "private"))) 

# re-order columns and use the tble data frame
     df2 <- tbl_df(df1[,c(1,12,3,13:15,7:11)])
        

# table list of studetns
# average score for each race and gender for each one of the classes ****
    df4 <- df2 %>% group_by(race, gender) %>% 
                          summarise_each(funs(mean), 
                          c(read,write,math, science, socst)
                           ) 
# round result numbers
df4[,-c(1:2)] <- round(df4[,-c(1:2)],0)

# display in table
DT::datatable(df4) 

#cross-classifying factors brekdown by race, gender, socio class
    with(df2, table(race, gender))
    with(df2, table(race, socioecon))

#subset blck female
  blk_fml <- subset(df2, race == "black" & gender == "female")
  
  
#subset not black female students  
  all_other <- df2[!(df2$race == "black" & df2$gender == "female"),]
  
# plot 1 all data
   p1 <- ggplot(data = df2, aes(x= math, y = science))
      p11 <- p1 + geom_jitter(color = "skyblue", size = 4) +
             #ggtitle("All students Math & Science score") +
             ggtitle("All Data - NOISE+SIGNAL") +
             theme_bw()    

#plot 2 - split blk_fml and layer together
   p2 <- ggplot(data = all_other, aes(x= math, y = science))
      p21 <- p2 + geom_jitter(color = "skyblue", size = 4) +
             geom_jitter(data = blk_fml, color = "orange", size = 4) +
             #ggtitle("Black female with all stuedents.") +
             ggtitle("Relevant Data - SIGNAL") +
             theme_bw()  

#plot 3 - just blk_fml
   p3 <- ggplot(data = blk_fml, aes(x= math, y = science))
     p31 <-  p3 + geom_jitter(data = blk_fml, color = "orange", size = 4) +
             ggtitle("Black female Math & Science ") +

# plot 4 - just all other
    p4 <-    ggplot(data = all_other, aes(x= math, y = science))

             ggtitle("All students score save for blk female") +
             theme_bw() 

# plot1  the entire population gray/black
grid.arrange(p11, p21, nrow=1, ncol=2)
 
  
#plot2  signal/noise split population from 
grid.arrange(p41, p31, nrow=1, ncol=2)


# plotly fig1 - blk fml low for math and science
 p <- ggplot(data = all_other, aes(x= math, y = science, shape = socioecon)) +
       geom_jitter(data = blk_fml, color = "orange", size = 4)
  
  ggplotly(
      p + geom_jitter(color = "gray", size = 1) +
      geom_jitter(data = blk_fml, color = "orange", size = 1) +

      )

# plotly fig1 - blk fml low for math and science
